misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that the final 'else' block will only execute for the conceptual 'F' range (0-59) defined in the problem, assuming the program will only handle inputs within the 0-100 range.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: The student fails to distinguish between the 'logical domain' of the problem (0-100) and the 'data type domain' of the variable (all integers). They do not realize that an 'else' block is a total logical complement of the preceding conditions; thus, it will catch any value not already handled, including values above 100 which are mathematically 'not below 60' but will still result in an 'F'.

misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that in an 'if-else if' sequence, each branch must explicitly define its own boundaries (e.g., checking both >= 80 and <= 89) to prevent the code from executing the wrong branch.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: The student does not fully grasp the mutually exclusive nature of 'if-else if' chains. They fail to realize that if control reaches an 'else if' block, all previous conditions (like 'grade >= 90') must have already evaluated to false, making the upper-bound check (e.g., 'grade <= 89') redundant.

misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that the final 'else' statement will only execute for values logically following the sequence (i.e., grades below 60), assuming that the program naturally constraints itself to the 0-100 range specified in the problem.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: The 'else' block in Java is a catch-all for any value that results in all previous 'if' and 'else if' conditions evaluating to false. Because the student explicitly capped the first condition at 'grade <= 100', any value greater than 100 (e.g., 105) will fail every check and fall into the 'else' block, resulting in a grade of 'F' despite not being below 60.

misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that each branch of an 'else if' chain must be fully self-contained, defining both the lower and upper bounds of a range as if the branches were independent of each other.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: The student does not realize that an 'else if' branch is only reached if all prior conditions are false. Consequently, the upper-bound checks (e.g., 'grade <= 89') are redundant because the previous 'if' statement (grade >= 90) already filtered out all values 90 and above.
